To save text to a local file in a JavaScript web app, you can use several approaches:

**Method 1: Using `Blob` and `URL.createObjectURL()`**

```javascript
const text = "Hello, World!";
const blob = new Blob([text], { type: 'text/plain' });
const url = URL.createObjectURL(blob);
const a = document.createElement('a');
a.href = url;
a.download = 'example.txt';
a.click();
```

In this method, we create a `Blob` object containing the text data. We then use `URL.createObjectURL()` to convert the `Blob` into a URL that can be used as a link target.

**Method 2: Using `FileSaver.js` library**

If you don't want to implement the blob API yourself, you can use the popular `FileSaver.js` library. This library provides a simple way to save files to the user's computer.

First, include the library in your HTML file:
```html
<script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/FileSaver.js/2.0.5/FileSaver.min.js"></script>
```

Then, use the following code:
```javascript
const text = "Hello, World!";
FileSaver.saveAs(text, 'example.txt');
```

**Method 3: Using `jszip` library**

Another approach is to use the `jszip` library to compress and save the text data as a ZIP archive.

First, include the library in your HTML file:
```html
<script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/jszip/5.0.1/jszip.min.js"></script>
```

Then, use the following code:
```javascript
const zip = new JSZip();
zip.file('example.txt', 'Hello, World!');
const blob = await zip.generateAsync({ type: 'blob' });
const url = URL.createObjectURL(blob);
// ...
```

**Method 4: Using `fetch` API**

If you're using modern browsers that support the Fetch API, you can use it to save the text data as a file.

First, create an HTML element and set its `href` attribute to a blob URL:
```html
<a id="save-file" href="#"></a>
```

Then, in your JavaScript code:
```javascript
const text = "Hello, World!";
fetch(window.URL.createObjectURL(new Blob([text], { type: 'text/plain' })))
  .then(response => response.blob())
  .then(blob => {
    const a = document.getElementById('save-file');
    a.href = URL.createObjectURL(blob);
    a.download = 'example.txt';
    a.click();
  });
```

Note that the `fetch` API approach requires modern browsers and may not work in older browsers.
